As much as w3schools has improved in recent years, it’s still not suitable for learning a language from. It’s good enough to reference on the odd occasion, but never religiously.
[/quote]I agree with this. w3schools isn’t a very good website to learn off of, but it does have some nice explanations on certain things that you may need to check up on.

Though, go with whichever you wish. Books, e-books, websites, whatever your preferences are. There’s plenty of options with a simple Google search.

Sorry, I don’t use w3schools.com but when I saw the topic I thought I would post what I know. I have a book on my bookself called HTML 3 Handbook, that’s what introduced me to html, I then ended up teaching myself PHP and Javascript.

Hahaha… Yes but that was when I was learning, a good 5 years ago. I am now upto date on HTML 5. No worries
[/quote]HTML 3 was still outdated 5 years ago.[/quote]

Sometimes you have to start somewhere. I just looked at the book, and it was HTML 3.2 (not that it makes a difference).
